## Report — Answers to Coursework Questions

---

### Part 1 — Question 1.1
**Explain the default lifecycle of a JAX-RS Resource class. How does this impact in-memory data management and how do you prevent data loss or race conditions?**

By default, JAX-RS creates a completely new instance of each Resource class for every HTTP request that arrives at the server. This behaviour is called the request-scoped lifecycle. Once the request finishes and a response has been sent, that resource object is discarded by the runtime. A fresh object is created for the next incoming request.

This creates an important challenge for data management. If data were stored as ordinary instance variables inside a resource class, all that data would be lost the moment each request completes. The next request would start with completely empty data, which is unacceptable for an API that needs to remember rooms, sensors, and readings across many requests.

To solve this, all persistent data in this project is stored inside a separate singleton class called `DataStore`. A singleton guarantees that only one single instance of that class is ever created during the entire lifetime of the running server. Because every request-scoped resource instance calls `DataStore.getInstance()` to access the same shared object, all requests read from and write to the same underlying data.

Inside `DataStore`, all data is held in `ConcurrentHashMap` structures rather than ordinary `HashMap`. This is necessary because many HTTP requests can arrive simultaneously from different users, meaning multiple threads will try to read and write data at the same time. An ordinary `HashMap` is not thread-safe and can become corrupted or cause unexpected errors in this situation. `ConcurrentHashMap` from `java.util.concurrent` is designed specifically to handle concurrent access safely, allowing multiple threads to operate on it at the same time without race conditions or data loss. This combination of the singleton pattern and `ConcurrentHashMap` ensures the API is both persistent and safe under high traffic.

---

### Part 1 — Question 1.2
**Why is HATEOAS considered a hallmark of advanced RESTful design? How does it benefit client developers compared to static documentation?**

HATEOAS stands for Hypermedia As The Engine Of Application State. It is considered a hallmark of advanced RESTful design because it makes an API self-describing and navigable, much like how a website works. When you visit a website you do not need to memorise every URL because the pages contain links guiding you to related content. HATEOAS applies exactly the same idea to APIs.

In this project, the discovery endpoint at `GET /api/v1` returns a JSON response that includes direct links to the primary resource collections, specifically `/api/v1/rooms` and `/api/v1/sensors`. A client application can start at this single entry point and follow the provided links to discover and use the rest of the API without needing any prior knowledge of the URL structure.

This benefits client developers in two important ways. First, it reduces the coupling between client and server. If a URL changes in a future version of the API, any client following the hypermedia links will automatically use the updated URL without code changes. A client with URLs hard-coded would simply break. Second, it solves the problem of documentation becoming outdated. Static documentation must be manually updated every time the API changes. Hypermedia responses are always accurate because they are generated live by the server itself.

---

### Part 2 — Question 2.1
**What are the implications of returning only IDs versus returning full room objects in a list response? Consider network bandwidth and client-side processing.**

When `GET /rooms` returns only a list of room IDs, the client must send a separate HTTP request for each ID to retrieve the full details of each room. If the campus has 100 rooms, this means 100 additional requests are required to display any useful information. This is known as the N+1 problem, and it significantly increases network traffic, latency, and server load.

Returning the full room objects in the list response solves this problem entirely. The client receives everything it needs in a single HTTP call. For applications such as campus management dashboards or automated building systems that need to process all room data at once, this is clearly the better approach.

The trade-off is that the initial response payload is larger when full objects are included. However, for most real-world use cases, receiving one larger response is far more efficient than making hundreds of small sequential requests. In this implementation, full room objects are returned in list responses because it is the more practical and performance-friendly design choice.

---

### Part 2 — Question 2.2
**Is the DELETE operation idempotent in your implementation? Provide a detailed justification.**

According to RFC 7231, an operation is considered idempotent if sending the same request multiple times produces the same server-side state as sending it once. Under this definition, the DELETE operation in this implementation is idempotent.

When a client sends `DELETE /rooms/ENG-205` for the first time, the room is found, removed from the data store, and the server returns 200 OK. If the exact same DELETE request is sent again, the room no longer exists, so the server returns 404 Not Found. In both cases, the state of the server is identical — the room ENG-205 does not exist.

It is important to understand that idempotency is about server-side state, not about the HTTP response code. The change in response code from 200 to 404 does not violate idempotency. No data is corrupted, no duplicate actions are performed, and no unintended side effects occur when the same DELETE request is sent multiple times. This is the standard and widely accepted behaviour for DELETE in professional RESTful API design.

---

### Part 3 — Question 3.1
**What are the technical consequences if a client sends data in a format such as text/plain when @Consumes(APPLICATION_JSON) is used?**

The `@Consumes(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)` annotation tells the JAX-RS framework that the endpoint will only accept request bodies formatted as `application/json`. When a client sends a POST request with a `Content-Type` header of `text/plain` or `application/xml`, the JAX-RS runtime performs content negotiation and detects the mismatch immediately.

As a result, JAX-RS automatically rejects the request and returns an HTTP 415 Unsupported Media Type response to the client. This happens entirely at the framework level before the request reaches any custom resource method code. The developer does not need to write additional validation logic to handle this case.

This behaviour is beneficial in two ways. First, it protects the application from receiving incorrectly formatted data that could cause unexpected errors or security issues in the business logic. Second, the 415 status code provides the client developer with a clear, precise message about exactly what went wrong — they simply need to set the correct `Content-Type: application/json` header in their request.

---

### Part 3 — Question 3.2
**Contrast @QueryParam with embedding the type in the URL path. Why is the query parameter approach superior for filtering?**

Using `@QueryParam` for filtering, such as `GET /api/v1/sensors?type=CO2`, is the correct RESTful approach. It clearly communicates the intention of filtering an existing collection based on an optional criterion. The base resource URL `/sensors` remains the same, and the query parameter simply narrows the results returned.

Embedding the filter value in the URL path, such as `/api/v1/sensors/type/CO2`, is semantically incorrect in RESTful design. Each segment of a REST URL path should identify a specific, uniquely addressable resource. The path segment `type/CO2` does not identify a unique resource — it describes a category within a collection, which is the wrong meaning for a path segment.

There are also strong practical reasons to prefer query parameters. They are optional by nature, so omitting the parameter returns the full unfiltered collection, which is natural expected behaviour. They also combine easily for multiple simultaneous filters, for example `?type=CO2&status=ACTIVE`. Achieving this with path segments would produce a confusing and unwieldy URL. For these reasons, `@QueryParam` is the industry standard for filtering and searching across resource collections in REST APIs.

---

### Part 4 — Question 4.1
**Discuss the architectural benefits of the Sub-Resource Locator pattern. How does it help manage complexity compared to putting all nested paths in one class?**

The Sub-Resource Locator pattern allows a JAX-RS resource class to delegate handling of a nested URL path to a separate, dedicated class. In this project, when a request arrives for `/sensors/{sensorId}/readings`, the `SensorResource` class does not handle it directly. Instead, it creates and returns an instance of `SensorReadingResource`, which takes full responsibility for all reading operations for that specific sensor.

The primary architectural benefit is a clear separation of responsibilities. `SensorResource` manages only sensor-level operations, while `SensorReadingResource` manages only reading history. This follows the Single Responsibility Principle. Each class is smaller, focused, and much easier to test and maintain independently.

Without this pattern, all sensor and reading logic would be placed inside one enormous resource class. As the API grows with more nested endpoints, such a class becomes very difficult to navigate and understand. Multiple developers working on the same file would regularly create merge conflicts, slowing down the team.

The sub-resource locator approach also naturally reflects the real-world data hierarchy. A reading belongs to a specific sensor, just as a sensor belongs to a specific room. Expressing this through class delegation makes the code architecture self-documenting and easy to extend in the future.

---

### Part 5 — Question 5.2
**Why is HTTP 422 more semantically accurate than 404 when a referenced resource is missing inside a valid JSON payload?**

HTTP 404 Not Found means the URL the client requested does not exist on the server. It is appropriate when a client requests `GET /api/v1/rooms/NONEXISTENT` and that room cannot be found.

The situation is different when a client sends a `POST` request to the valid URL `/api/v1/sensors` with correctly formatted JSON, but the `roomId` value inside the body refers to a room that does not exist. Here the URL is valid and the endpoint is working correctly. The problem is not with the URL — it is with the semantic content of the data inside the request body.

HTTP 422 Unprocessable Entity was specifically designed for this scenario. It communicates to the client that the request was received successfully, the URL exists, and the JSON is syntactically correct, but the server cannot process it because the data contains a logically invalid reference. This is far more informative than a 404 because it tells the developer exactly what kind of error occurred — a semantic validation failure inside the payload — and points them directly to the fix, which is to supply a `roomId` that actually exists in the system.

---

### Part 5 — Question 5.3
**Why is HTTP 403 Forbidden the correct response when a POST reading is attempted on a MAINTENANCE sensor?**

HTTP 403 Forbidden is used here because the client's request is perfectly valid in every technical sense — the sensor exists, the URL is correct, and the JSON body is well-formed. However, the server refuses to process the request because of the current operational state of the resource. A sensor marked as MAINTENANCE has been deliberately taken offline by an administrator. It is physically disconnected and is not capable of accepting new readings.

Using 404 would be incorrect because the sensor does exist in the system. Using 400 Bad Request would also be wrong because there is nothing wrong with the way the request was formed. HTTP 403 is the most semantically accurate choice because it clearly signals that the server understands the request completely but is refusing it based on business rules and the current state of the resource. The appropriate action for the client is to change the sensor status back to ACTIVE before attempting to post readings again.

---

### Part 5 — Question 5.4
**From a cybersecurity standpoint, what are the risks of exposing internal Java stack traces to external API consumers?**

Exposing raw Java stack traces in API error responses is a well-known and serious security vulnerability. When an unhandled exception results in a full stack trace being returned to the client, it provides an attacker with a detailed map of the application's internal structure.

The first major risk is library and version fingerprinting. Stack traces contain fully qualified class names such as `org.glassfish.jersey.server.ServerRuntime` or `com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper`. An attacker uses these names to identify the exact versions of third-party libraries and searches public vulnerability databases such as the CVE database for known exploits in those specific versions.

The second risk is file system path exposure. Stack traces often include absolute server file paths such as `C:/Users/server/webapps/SmartCampusAPI`. This reveals the internal directory structure of the server, which assists attackers in planning directory traversal or file inclusion attacks.

The third risk is internal logic disclosure. The sequence of method calls in a stack trace reveals how the application processes requests internally. This helps attackers identify code weak points and craft targeted inputs designed to exploit them, for example through injection attacks or by deliberately triggering specific error conditions.

The `GlobalExceptionMapper` in this project addresses all of these risks. It catches every unexpected exception using `ExceptionMapper<Throwable>`, logs the full technical details securely on the server side only, and returns a simple, generic HTTP 500 message to the client containing no sensitive information whatsoever.

---

### Part 5 — Question 5.5
**Why is it better to use JAX-RS filters for cross-cutting concerns like logging rather than inserting Logger.info() statements manually inside every resource method?**

Manually inserting `Logger.info()` statements inside every individual resource method is a poor practice for several important reasons.

First, it violates the DRY principle — Do Not Repeat Yourself. The same boilerplate logging code would need to be written identically across every single method in the project. This increases the size of the codebase and makes it harder to read.

Second, manual logging is unreliable because it depends on the developer remembering to add it. If a new endpoint is created and the developer forgets, that endpoint silently goes unmonitored. This creates gaps in the log history that make diagnosing problems very difficult.

Third, if the logging format ever needs to change — for example to add a request ID or timestamp — every single method in the project must be found and updated individually. This is time-consuming, error-prone, and likely to produce inconsistencies.

JAX-RS filters solve all of these problems. By implementing `ContainerRequestFilter` and `ContainerResponseFilter` in a single `LoggingFilter` class, every HTTP request and response is automatically logged with complete consistency. This works regardless of which resource class handles the request. The resource classes themselves remain clean and focused on business logic only. This follows the Separation of Concerns principle, which is a foundational principle of professional and maintainable software design.
